## Supplemental Security Income (SSI)

Supplemental Security Income (SSI) pays monthly benefits to people with limited income who have a qualifying disability. Caregivers of children who are blind, deaf, drug affected, diagnosed with medical fragility, a disability, or receive special education services are eligible for SSI benefits. 

{% Callout %}While the child is a dependent of the state of Washington, the Department will receive SSI on behalf of the child.{% endCallout %}

You are **eligible** to receive SSI for a qualifying child:

<ul class="icon-list">
{% IconListItem "yes" %}If you are informally/independently caring for a child (i.e., the child is not in foster care){% endIconListItem %}

{% IconListItem "yes" %}Once a child’s dependency ends, e.g. if you have become a child’s guardian or adoptive parent{% endIconListItem %}
</ul>

You are **not eligible** if:

<ul class="icon-list">
{% IconListItem "no" %}The child is in foster care{% endIconListItem %}
</ul>



